summary: I hope DnP aren’t using the hiatus as a way to make people lose interest in the gaming channel so they can eventually call it...
question: I hope DnP aren’t using the hiatus as a way to make people lose interest in the gaming channel so they can eventually call it quits. If they were to quit and this had been their plan all along I’d be pretty upset that they hadn’t been honest with their audience.   Having said that everyone does need a creative break from time to time and I know it’s hard for them to put a time frame on as to when they’ll feel ready to come back. But I feel like they’ve been hinting at bringing things to an end.
answer: If that did turn out to be the case, I would be upset, but only because they have continued to take their audience’s money in the mean time, while giving them a false sense of hope, and I think, especially considering their demographics, that would be a really sleezey thing to do. I would lose so much respect for both of them and would hope that they were hit with the backlash they would rightfully deserve. I’m still giving them the benefit of the doubt on this, based on the fact that they have never really done anything to make me question their character to that extent before, but I definitely wouldn’t give either of them the benefit of my wallet unless I had some more concrete answers.

summary: people in the phandom depend on dan and phil too much. like i get people who may have been 'saved' by their videos, that must...
question: people in the phandom depend on dan and phil too much. like i get people who may have been 'saved' by their videos, that must create an emotional bond, but other people who just watch them  for fun and become obsessed with them and dramatically say they would die if the gaming channel ended and about how they miss them so much, like no offense but dont you have other hobbies or other youtubers to watch? their whole lives revolve dan and phil and it cant be good for their mental health
answer: I agree with this completely. As an audience, we have parasocial relationships with Dan and Phil, not real ones. We interact with content they put out on the internet, but they don’t know us, and we don’t know them outside of their personas. They market themselves as internet friends, but they aren’t our friends. From what I have read, there is evidence to support the fact that parasocial relationships can actually be beneficial for people psychologically, especially those who don’t have a lot of social interaction otherwise. However, I think it is also very easy to get overly-attached and misinterpret the situation, especially for young viewers.
